                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.003/711a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cunningham</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-06-03T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 3, 1931—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>For the Minister: During the redrafting of articles in the Department’s April 27
                    draft proposals, Mr. Weigh of the Chinese Legation endeavored to revise in the
                    exchange of notes the provision regarding the Chinese legal counselor in order
                    to give him “the same functions as the foreign legal counselors.” According to
                    Weigh’s information, he stated that the Chinese-British negotiators have arrived
                    at such an accord as to this point. Since the Department has understood that the
                    Chinese legal counselor was desired for the sake of <pb facs="0983" n="873"
                        xml:id="pg_873"/> liaison, will you please ask the British negotiators and
                    report whether the statement by Weigh is correct.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
